  DISEASES & MEDICINE
============================================================

Disease:     Malaria
Type:        Parasitic
Pathogen:    Plasmodium falciparum
Transmission:Mosquito bite
Symptoms:    Fever, chills, sweating cycles
Treatment:   Artemisinin combination therapy
Deaths/yr:   0.619M
Vaccine:     Yes (RTS,S approved 2021)
Discovered:  1880

Disease:     Tuberculosis
Type:        Bacterial
Pathogen:    M. tuberculosis
Transmission:Airborne droplets
Symptoms:    Persistent cough, night sweats
Treatment:   6-9 month antibiotics
Deaths/yr:   1.6M
Vaccine:     Yes (BCG, partial)
Discovered:  1882

Disease:     HIV/AIDS
Type:        Viral
Pathogen:    HIV
Transmission:Sexual contact, blood
Symptoms:    Flu-like; then AIDS symptoms
Treatment:   Antiretroviral therapy (ART)
Deaths/yr:   0.65M
Vaccine:     No (in development)
Discovered:  1983

============================================================
  QUESTION & ANSWER PAIRS
============================================================

Q1: What is plate tectonics?
A1: Earth's crust is divided into tectonic plates that move
     on the mantle. Their interactions create earthquakes,
     volcanoes, mountains, and ocean trenches over millions
     of years.

Q2: What is the periodic table?
A2: The periodic table organizes 118 elements by atomic
     number. Elements in the same column share chemical
     properties. Rows are periods; columns are groups.

Q3: What is the internet?
A3: The internet is a global network of interconnected
     computers using TCP/IP protocols. It began as ARPANET
     in 1969 and became public with the World Wide Web in
     1994.

Q4: What is the water cycle?
A4: Water evaporates from oceans/lakes, rises and condenses
     into clouds, falls as precipitation, and flows back via
     rivers and groundwater. Driven by solar energy.

Q5: What is a programming language?
A5: A programming language is a formal set of instructions
     for computers. High-level languages (Python, Java) are
     human-readable; low-level (Assembly) are closer to
     machine code.

